        "title":"UK \u201ccommitted\u201d to GB Energy despite funding\u00a0cut reports",
        "subtitle":"\n              (Montel) The UK government has told Montel it remains \u201cfully committed\u201d to GB Energy, following media reports that the Treasury is considering cutting funding for the state-owned power company.\n            ",
        "body":"\nGB Energy was set up in 2024 to spearhead the nation\u2019s green energy push, but the Financial Times reported on Friday morning that the Treasury is facing \u201cmounting pressure\u201d to reduce funding to the company.\n\u201cPivot towards defence spending\u201dCiting \u201cpeople familiar with the discussions\u201d, the FT reported that the government is seeking to \u201cpivot towards greater defence spending\u201d following recent geopolitical developments involving the war in Ukraine, and that GB Energy may be on the chopping block.\nThe UK government initially pledged GBP 8.3bn of funding for GB Energy up to 2029, but only GBP 100m was earmarked for it in October\u2019s autumn budget.\nThe UK government, however, told Montel it is \u201cfully committed to the GBP 8.3bn for GB Energy, which is at the heart of our mission to make Britain a clean energy superpower\u201d.\nIt added that\u00a0GB Energy is \u201cmaking rapid progress\u201d by \u201cmaking Juergen Maier the start-up chair, confirming Aberdeen as HQ, progressing the Great British Energy Bill, and creating an unprecedented partnership with The Crown Estate, which has the potential to leverage up to \u00a360bn\u00a0of private investment into the UK\u2019s drive for energy independence\u201d.\n",
